Bring a #large pot{} of water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Trim and thinly
slice @scallions{2}(trimmed and thinly sliced), separating whites from greens.
Roughly chop @cashews{1%ounce}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{3%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add @chopped chicken breast{10%ounce}; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.
Cook, stirring occasionally, until cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn
off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add broccoli;
season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring frequently, until browned and
tender, ~{4-7%minutes}.

Add scallion whites, @shredded carrots{4%ounce}, and @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}.
Cook, stirring frequently and lowering heat if browning too quickly, until
veggies are just tender and fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: If pan seems dry, add a drizzle of oil.

While veggies cook, in a #small bowl{}, combine @sweet Thai chili sauce{2%ounce},
@Vidalia onion paste{1/2%ounce}, half the @rice wine vinegar{5%teaspoon},
half the @soy sauce{2%tablespoon}, and 1⁄4 cup water.

> For 4 servings, use all the vinegar, all the soy sauce, and 1/2 cup water instead.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to #pot{}. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Drain noodles, shaking off any excess water, and transfer to pan with veggies.
Add soy-chili mixture, half the cashews, and @butter{1%tablespoon}. Toss until
butter has melted and noodles are thoroughly coated, ~{30-60%seconds}. Taste
and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Add chicken to pan along with noodles.

Divide lo mein between #shallow bowls{}; garnish with scallion greens and
remaining cashews. Serve.